observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipality prepare and submit the following
documents to the audit team for the latter’s evaluation of disposal of the
unserviceable assets:
 Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property of General Form
#17(A);
 Checklist for Unserviceable Equipment: Vehicles/Heavy Equipment;
 Checklist of Property for Disposal
 Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) or General Form No. 05-0768;
 Equipment Ledger Card of General Form #32(A);
 Report of Waste Materials or General Form #46(A);
 Invoice Receipt of Property or General Form #30(A), if donation/transfer of
property;
 In-house appraisal indicating the basis of valuation, approaches used to
come-up with the appraised value; description of the subject properties;
 Authenticated copy of latest vehicle registration (LTO OR and CR);
 Current colored photographs of the properties duly signed by the agency
concerned;
Likewise, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant review the nature of the
items recorded under Power Supply Systems account and make the necessary
reclassification, if necessary.

Management’s Comments:
On the day of the exit conference, the Municipal Treasurer commented that they are
starting to collate the documents needed for evaluation of disposal of unserviceable
assets.

Considering the repetitive findings on LDRRM, we recommended that the LDRRM Council headed by the Municipal Mayor to:
 require the LDRRMO of the diligent performance of his duties and responsibilities by determining/assessing and documenting the identified disaster risks in the Municipality and its barangays to be able to plan disaster-responsive activities and maximize the annual LDRRMF Plan and verify the actual need for the purchase of disaster equipment and supplies allotted with current and continuing appropriations; and
 resolve in the upcoming council meeting any necessary amendments/updates to the LDRRM Investment Plan including only programs and activities that the Council intends to implement based on disaster risk assessment and verified information from the LDRRMP on pursuing the purchase activities existing in the plan. Consider providing trainings given the available LDRRMF funds that could better inform and improve disaster resiliency of barangay constituents through the help of barangay officials;

We recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee:
during canvass, require the supplier to indicate the distinct description of the item they are offering;
indicate in the Purchase Order the detailed specifications as agreed with the supplier such as the information required by the above-mentioned COA Circular;
explain the difference in the prices of same items procured from the same supplier in separate transactions; and
for small value procurement, the requirement under Section 53.9 of RA9184 and the documentary requirements under Annex H of this Code shall be strictly complied.
We also recommended that the assigned Inspector ensure that the delivered goods are in compliance with the agreed specifications in the approved Purchase Order.

We recommended that:
the BAC submit the lacking financial and eligibility requirements of the winning bidder and provide basis for awarding subject contracts to an ineligible bidder;
strict compliance with the requirements of the ITB postings in PhilGEPs be observed to attract more interested bidders that would result in a competitive bidding in order to obtain the best quality and lowest price to the advantage of the Municipal Government;
all provisions applicable to the contract agreement be included in the Bid Data Sheet and Special 

Conditions of the Contract in compliance with the prescribed Philippine Bidding documents;
the contract time be determined and specified in the contract agreement and in other bidding documents as required so delays in the part of the contractor could be determined;
the BAC ensure that sufficient warranty of 30%, if in the form of a surety bond callable upon demand, be posted by the contractor after the completion and final acceptance of the project; and
the BAC be extra cautious in the screening/review of bidding/supporting papers of the bidders to ensure that projects are awarded to eligible bidders.
